 paint for a living in early modern England. It considers the origins of these painters as well as their geographical location, the varieties of their expertise, and the personnel and spatial arrangements of their workshops. Engagingly written, the book captures a sense of mobility and exchange between England and the continent through the considerable influence of stranger-painters, undermining traditional notions about the insular character of this phase in the history of English art. By showing how painters responded to the greater political, religious, and economic upheavals of the time, the study refracts the history of England itself through the lens of this particular occupation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aPaintersxEmploymentxHistoryy16th centuryzEngland. 0aPaintersxEmploymentxHistoryy17th centuryzEngland. 0aPaintersxEmploymentxHistoryyTo 1500zEngland. 0aPaintersxHistoryy16th centuryzEngland. 0aPaintersxHistoryy17th centuryzEngland. 0aPaintersxHistoryyTo 1500zEngland. 0aPainterszGreat BritainxSocial conditions. 0aPaintingzGreat BritainxHistory. 4aArt & Architecture. 4aEarly Modern History. 7aART / European.2bisacsh  aCharles I.  aEarly Modern England.  aEnglish Reformation.  aHenry VIII.  aJames I.  aLondon, Chester.  aQueen Elizabeth.  aRenaissance.  aStuart monarchy.  aapprenticeship.  aart.  acoats of arms.  aguilds.  aheralds.  aiconoclasm.  aimmigrants.  aincome.  aoccupations.  apainter-stainer.  apainter.  apatronage.  apicture.  aportrait.  aprovincial England.  areligious imagery.  astained glass.  atrades.  avernacular culture.  avisual imagery.  awall painting.  aworkshops.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311143099740uhttp